# Frontend Error Handling

Server action errors must always surface as Sonner toasts, never as inline React state.

## Pattern

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — inline error state
const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null)
const result = await someServerAction()
if (!result.ok) {
  setError(result.error)
  return
}
// ...
{error && <p className="text-destructive">{error}</p>}

// ✅ GOOD — Sonner toast
import { toast } from "sonner"
const result = await someServerAction()
if (!result.ok) {
  toast.error(result.error)
  return
}
```

## Rules

- Import `toast` from `"sonner"` in any client component that calls server actions
- Call `toast.error(result.error)` on `{ ok: false }` responses
- Call `toast.success("...")` for meaningful success confirmations
- Never use `useState` to store server action error strings for display
- Never render `<p className="text-destructive">{error}</p>` for server errors
- Validation errors that are field-specific (e.g. "text cannot be empty") may remain inline in forms
